ricable from the political project of black liberation, Castor illustrates the ways in which Ifá/Orisha beliefs and practices offer Trinidadians the means to strengthen belonging throughout the diaspora, access past generations, heal historical wounds, and envision a decolonial future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aBlack powerzTrinidad and TobagozTrinidad. 0aBlackszTrinidad and TobagozTrinidadxReligion. 0aCultszTrinidad and TobagozTrinidadxAfrican influences. 0aIfa (Religion)zTrinidad and TobagozTrinidad. 0aOrisha religionzTrinidad and TobagozTrinidad. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822372585.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles